          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">3:188 hostage-prisoner swap</h2> 
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/3-188-hostage-prisoner-swap.png" alt="Hamas fighters escort Israeli hostages (left to right) Ohad Ben Ami, Or Levy, and Eli Sharabi before handing them over to a Red Cross team in Deir el-Balah, central Gaza" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            Hamas fighters escort Israeli hostages (left to right) Ohad Ben Ami, Or Levy, and Eli Sharabi before handing them over to a Red Cross team in Deir el-Balah, central Gaza. Credits: AFP

          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Fifth prisoner swap under Israel-Hamas ceasefire deal takes place as Israel withdraws troops from key Gaza corridors. Clashes escalate in the West Bank.</strong></p> 

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Hamas released three Israeli hostages on Saturday in an exchange at Gaza’s Deir al-Balah area. In return, Israel freed 183 Palestinian prisoners. This marks the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-02-2025-h1-1-fifth-exchange" target="_blank">fifth exchange</a> under the ceasefire deal, which began on January 19. So far, 16 Israeli hostages have been freed in exchange for over 566 Palestinian prisoners, with negotiations for the next phase ongoing.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">An Israeli delegation arrived in Qatar on Sunday for further talks. <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-02-2025-h1-2-indirect-negotiations" target="_blank">Indirect negotiations</a> between Israel and Hamas on the next stage of the ceasefire are set to begin this week. Sources indicate that the Israeli delegation will only address technical matters rather than larger issues, such as post-war governance in Gaza. The stability of the ceasefire hangs in the balance as Israel backs Trump’s Gaza <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-02-2025-h1-3-takeover-proposal" target="_blank">takeover proposal</a>.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5; filter: blur(5px);">Separately, Israel withdrew from the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-02-2025-h1-4-netzarim-corridor" target="_blank">Netzarim Corridor</a>, restoring movement between northern and southern Gaza as per the ceasefire terms. However, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-02-2025-h1-5-violence-escalated" target="_blank">violence escalated</a> in the occupied West Bank, where Hamas and the Palestinian Jihad attacked Israeli forces in the Nur Shams refugee camp. Israeli military raids in the area recently killed two Palestinian women, one of whom was eight months pregnant. 
</p>
        </mj-text>
